table-0218-430.caption: 1830–1911
data: Indians massacred eighteen members and relatives of the Killough family in Texas.
During the Seminole Wars, Florida Seminole attacked and destroyed an Indian Key settlement, killing 13 inhabitants, including noted horticulturist Dr. Henry Perrine.
Volunteer Rangers under Colonel Moore massacred 140 Comanches (men, women and children) in their village on the Colorado and captured 35 others (mostly small children).
Parker, Horace, The Historic Valley of Temecula. The Temecula Massacre 24 pages, Paisano Press (1971), 286593

In response to a New Mexican-instigated uprising in Taos, American troops attacked the Pueblo of Taos, using a howitzer to shell the village church. The Americans slaughtered nearly 150 Indians within and near the church. Between 25 and 30 prisonners were shot by firing squads.
White settlers led by a notorious Indian hunter named Ben Wright massacred 41 Modocs during a "peace parley".

US forces attacked and killed an unreported number of Indians in the Four Creeks area (Tulare County, California) in what was referred to by officers as "our little difficulty" and "the chastisement they have received".
Near Sinker Creek Idaho, 11 persons of the last wagon train of the year were killed and several others were subsequently killed. Some that escaped the initial massacre starved to death
Apaches massacred hundreds of Americans and Mexicans in and around Cookes Canyon, New Mexico over the course of several months.
Indians attacked an Arizona stagecoach, killing the driver and his five passengers, leaving two wounded survivors.
3 settlers killed, 1 woman abducted, apparently by Indians at Middle Fork of Walnut Creek, Kansas

table-0218-441.caption: Types
data: hose is a fabric-covered, flexible hose used to bring water from the fire pumper to the nozzle. This hose ranges in nominal inside diameter from and is designed to operate at pressures up to about psi (kPa). The standard length is ft (m).

are large-diameter, fabric-covered, flexible hoses used to bring water from a distant hydrant to the fire pumper or to relay water from one pumper to another over a long distance. These hoses range in nominal inside diameter from . They are designed to operate at pressures up to about psi (kPa) for the smaller diameters and up to psi (kPa) for the larger diameters. The standard length is ft (m).

is a fabric-covered, flexible hose used to fight fires in grass, brush, and trees where a lightweight hose is needed in order to maneuver it over steep or rough terrain. Forestry hose comes in nominal inside diameters and is designed to operate at pressures up to about psi (kPa). The standard length is ft (m).

is a rubber-covered, thick-walled, flexible hose used to fight small fires. It retains its round cross-section when it is not under pressure and is usually carried on a reel on the fire pumper, rather than being stored flat. Booster hose comes in nominal inside diameters and is designed to operate at pressures up to psi (kPa). The standard length is ft (m).

sometimes called hard suction, is usually a rubber-covered, semi-rigid hose with internal metal reinforcements. It is used to suck water out of unpressurized sources, such as ponds or rivers, by means of a vacuum. Suction hose ranges in nominal inside diameter from . The standard length is ft (m).

During the War of 1812, twenty four settlers, including fifteen children, were massacred by a war party of Native Americans (mostly Shawnee, but possibly including some Delawares and Potawatomis) in a surprise attack on a small village located in what is today Scott County, Indiana.

Mari has a dream where she drowns next to the ship she saw the previous night, and is awakened by Michiko. While eating breakfast, Mari is scorned by Hagino's admirers. Outside, Hagino communicates with Tsubael, the operator of an Arume ship named Blue, who addresses Hagino as her superior. In school, Mari is welcomed by her class, although she finds sitting next to Hagino intolerable. Back in their dorm, Hagino arranges for her to be in the same room as Mari, much to Mari's distress. When a hologram of Tsubael appears and speaks to Hagino, Mari sees it, and when Hagino touches Mari, Hagino begins screaming in pain.

Another Arume ship begins to inquire as to the presence of Hagino's ship, and as a result, Tsubael poses as Hagino's parent to allow Hagino to return to her craft, Blue. At school, Yūko Sugawara, Mari's homeroom teacher, causes a scandal when she is given a ride by the headmaster, and is forced to deal with the catcalls of the student body. During classes, Mari daydreams about Hagino. When Mari and Michiko return to the dorm, Mari is forced to help with the monthly student cooking session, and her lack of cooking skills creates a disaster. As she goes to bed, Mari thinks of Hagino, as Hagino reminisces in Blue. Hagino then surfaces Blue to meet her superior's vessel.

Hagino reports to her "Master Commander" Shivariel, who addresses Hagino as "Ekaril," that she was out of contact for five years due to a malfunction in Blue ' s Emiru Force Drive. She explains this was the cause of the incident in Kamioki Island, in which one of her crew members died, along with the Arume landing party and all of the island's inhabitants except Mari. Azanael, a crew member on Shivariel's ship who lost her lover Onomil in the incident, attempts to attack Hagino, but is restrained. At the school, Mari talks with Michiko, who reveals that she writes stories to fully express herself. Akane Kawashima, an upperclassman, treats the two to lunch in the town, where she reveals her ambition to become a cook and asks Mari to be more open with Hagino. However, Mari is kidnapped by thugs just as Shivariel dispatches a probe to retrieve Mari, whom she is interested in. However, Hagino destroys the probe, causing a tearful Mari to embrace her in response.

In the dorm, Hagino and Tsubael explain their Arume nature to a perplexed Mari. Later at school, Yūko attempts to ask Michiko to write a script for the school festival, and Mari later pushes her to do so. Shivariel dispatches a ship to attack Blue, which is barely able to survive the subsequent assault. In his office, the headmaster collapses and is sent to the hospital, and Akane, the headmaster's daughter, is pressed to visit him by Mari. As Akane prepares to leave, she is discovered by Hagino, and Mari, Michiko, and Hiroko attempt to cover for her. Mari then tells Hagino that she helped Akane because she wanted to help her be with someone important to her. As the group sleeps, Tsubael manages to critically damage the opposing ship under Hagino's instructions, and afterward, Hagino reflects on Mari's statement about having someone important in one's life.

Mari fails the semester exam and is forced to study with Yūko in order to prepare for the exam. Mari studies diligently and extracts a promise from Yūko to join her at the fireworks festival if she passes. Due to Hagino's insubordination, Shivariel sends two ships to destroy Blue. Meanwhile, Mari overhears that Yūko is a special investigator attempting to uncover Mari's memories of the incident five years prior. She runs away into the woods followed by Yūko, and the two are attacked by Azaneal. Hagino arrives and defeats Azaneal, just as Tsubael has Blue cripple its opponents. Following this, Mari asks Yūko to stay at the school, even though Yūko was planning to leave due to her cover being blown.

Mari, Hagino, Michiko, and Akane go to Hiroko's house one day during the summer vacation, and enjoy swimming in the ocean. However, when Hagino goes to retrieve a shell, it begins raining, and Mari desperately calls out for Hagino. Meanwhile, Hiroko's pregnant sister goes into labor, and the four girls are forced to take care of Hiroko's baby niece in the process. Although they encounter problems, such as changing the baby's diaper and feeding her, they manage to calm her. Later, Hagino gives Tsubael the shell she found as a gift. As Hiroko returns to the house to retrieve the baby, she finds the four girls asleep, Mari and Hagino next to one another.

Michiko begins to have increasing pressure put on her to finish the script for the school festival, and she is still unable to write anything. Meanwhile, Tsubael takes a tour through Hagino's dorm and is exasperated at the activities humans indulge in. On Hagino's orders, she allows Azanael out of her cell, and Azanael goes to Onomil's room. Afterward, Tsubael shows her a recording of Onomil's last moments: she sacrifices her life to save the ship for Hagino's sake. Michiko finally succumbs to stress and runs away, and when she returns, collapses while apologizing to Yūko. While in bed, she sees Mari, Hagino, and Tsubael walking together, and is inspired to start writing the play.

Afterward, Tsubael shows her a recording of Onomil's last moments: she sacrifices her life to save the ship for Hagino's sake. Michiko finally succumbs to stress and runs away, and when she returns, collapses while apologizing to Yūko. While in bed, she sees Mari, Hagino, and Tsubael walking together, and is inspired to start writing the play.

Mari wakes Michiko in the morning after she finished most of the script, and her script is received well by the class. To gather materials, Mari and Hagino go into town to purchase them. Meanwhile, Azanael watches them with Tsubael, incredulous as to Hagino's objectives. After finishing, Mari and Hagino go on the ferris wheel, where Mari asks Hagino if they can walk home. As they do so, Mari is injured and due to the rain, the two stay in an abandoned restaurant for the night. Mari and Hagino huddle together under a blanket, and Mari remembers that Hagino saved her life five years prior. However, as Mari tearfully embraces Hagino, Azanael is incensed that Hagino saved Mari's life instead of Onomil's.

Michiko finishes the script, and Yūko selects her to be the director of the play. As a result, she assigns the actors' roles, and Mari is uncomfortable in her part, especially after Hagino acts her part seemingly perfectly. Afterward, everyone in the dorm helps in preparing the props for the play, and Hagino, inspired by Michiko's statement to have the courage to be open, invites Mari onto Blue. After the two enjoy a ride, the ship begins to suffer system failure, and Azanael takes Mari away. However, Azanael reveals that Hagino was responsible for the deaths of everyone in the incident five years ago, including Mari's parents. As Azanael escapes, Mari stares blankly at a tearful Hagino.

Tsubael takes Mari back to the surface, and implores her not to blame Hagino. Back at the school, Mari finds that she lacks any drive to participate in the play, resulting in a furious reaction from Michiko. Meanwhile, Hagino weeps in Onomil's room, and is confronted with an image of her, who tells Hagino not to blame herself. Azanael then returns to Shivariel's ship, and finds that Shivariel is sending multiple ships to destroy Blue. At the school, Mari converses with Hagino's projection, and, after seeing Arume ships dot the sky, she elicits a promise from Hagino to return to finish their talk. However, their conversation is seen by Yūko. Hagino and Tsubael barely manage to survive the assault, with a key system coming online due to the phantom Onomil's efforts. At Shivariel's ship, Azanael discovers that the explosion on the Blue five years ago that killed Onomil was not an accident.

As the students begin to prepare for the school festival, Hagino returns. The cast of the play then comes out in their costumes, and Michiko gains permission to prepare the hall overnight. Hagino is invited to Yūko's classroom, where Yūko confronts Hagino at gunpoint, and asks her intentions. Hagino reveals she wishes to protect the planet against the Arume invasion. On Shivariel's ship, Azanael accuses Shivariel of having deliberately caused the explosion of Blue ' s Emiru Force Drive, in order to cover up her test of a new thought-wave weapon on the Arume and humans upon Kamioki Island. Azanael attempts to assassinate Shivariel, but kills only a fake Shivariel created with her new weapon. Shivariel then uses the weapon to materialize Azanael's fears, allowing the crew to shoot her, but Azanael manages to escape. At the festival, Mari's grandmother arrives, and Mari tells her she has begun to realize why her grandmother sent her to the school. Afterward, Mari converses with Hagino, and after admonishing Hagino for not telling her about the explosion on Kamioki Island earlier, the two admit their love for one another.

A Drop in the Ocean Episode 13 aired in Japan without a subtitle.

As Michiko adds the finishing touches to the play, Mari and Hagino, holding hands, approach her, and Michiko rejoices at the pair's reconciliation. Meanwhile, the Arume invasion of Earth begins, and the human military forces are overwhelmed, but Blue manages to destroy several Arume ships. At the school, the play begins; however, Shivariel starts to bomb the school. As the students evacuate, Hagino reveals she is an Arume to those present, and travels back to Blue. Blue is nearly destroyed in the subsequent onslaught of Arume ships, but is saved by Azanael. Mari runs to the docks to see Blue, and tearfully cries for Hagino as Blue flies off. Hagino ejects Tsubael from the ship and rams Shivariel's ship as it is about to fire its main weapon, destroying both ships. Hagino dies while reciting her lines from the play and her name, and Mari silently asks her sacrifice to be a sign of hope to the whole planet. Thirty years in the future, a shuttle containing Michiko approaches an Arume ship on a peace mission, while Michiko states that everything will be fine.

data: New recruit DC Stevie Moss brings a breath of fresh air to CID with her positive and lively outlook – though she manages to upset Mickey on her first day by stealing his parking space. Her first case involves a professional footballer, Jem Archer, who is forced to admit he is gay after his closet lover, Robbie Nash, is run over in a hit-and-run incident involving his fiancee. Suspicion falls on the player's manager Ernie Rosen, who also happens to be his prospective father-in-law and anxious to avoid the shame of a scandal in the family, but Sally uncovers evidence to suggest he is covering for someone even closer to home.

A student, Mandy Glover, reports being attacked in the park on her way home from the bar where she works, but a history of false allegations casts doubt on her story until the Sun Hill watch realise they have a dangerous and increasingly reckless maniac on their hands. Kezia recognises a familiar face on the list of suspects, and her instinct proves correct when Mandy receives a death threat - but, in the absence of evidence, Sally agrees to go undercover at the bar where she works to catch the culprit.

An eleven-year-old boy is abducted by a hooded man in a shopping centre, leading to fears a copycat child killer, mimicking the kidnap and murder of three young boys twenty years ago, is on the loose in Sun Hill. Mike Wilson becomes prime suspect when a shrine to convicted murderer Linda Johnson and her deceased partner in crime, Alaister Haigh, is found at his home, but as Neil grows closer to his informant in her cell, he discovers the case is not nearly as straightforward as it first appeared.

Heaton calls a press conference to tackle the growing media interest in Linda Johnson's involvement in the Clark abduction case, unwittingly attracting the attention of her victims' relatives, Tommy and Pete Barclay, as well. The case takes a shocking turn when the abductor is revealed to be an important figure from Linda's past, and when a ransom note mysteriously appears, demanding Linda drop off £10,000 in the park to secure Dean's release, the ensuing sting operation threatens to end in tragedy.

Smithy helps the victim of a knife attack, Tito Morientes, on the Jasmine Allen estate, and renews acquaintance with Carly Samuels, a girl whom he had helped in the past. Smithy battles in vain to save Carly's life following the shooting, and struggles with his feelings back at the station when he is tasked as the family liaison officer. A mobile unit is set up on the estate to help with community problems in light of the gang violence, and Beth's decision to bring in Harry the dog proves a winner with Nate when he realises how popular he is with the girls. Meanwhile, local gang member Maurice Thompson provides false evidence regarding the shooting, and Carly's best friend Alisha informs Smithy that Marlon Reed is on a mission to kill Tito Morientes.

After a local health centre is broken into, Diane and Nate find Dr Adam Tyler badly beaten inside. CCTV footage shows Brendan Connor, a local drug addict, taking supplies from the drugs cabinet, and it's not long before Brendon admits to taking the drugs. When questioned, however, he is adamant that he didn't beat up the doctor. The team then find out that the beating is linked to illegal operations that one of his colleagues, Rachel Cartwright, has been performing. Meanwhile, Carly's mother, Leanne tries to take her own life after a psychic claims that she 'saw' Tito Morientes get into the car used in the drive-by shooting, but nobody is brave enough to give evidence leading to a prosecution.

Carly's funeral descends into chaos as the crowd chant 'murderer' at chief suspect Tito Morientes, who turns up unexpectedly. When a gunshot shatters the glass of the hearse, the team work to restore order in order to give Carly a decent send-off. When order is restored, Leanne delivers a moving eulogy about her daughter, which has a marked effect on Alisha, who eventually breaks down under further questioning, and tells CID what she knows about the murder - breaking Tito's alibi, and confirming who is responsible for her best friend's death. Meanwhile, Neil decides to take some well-earned leave to sort out events in his personal life.

Tito Morientes is arrested on the testimony of Alisha Danniels for shooting Carly Samuels, but with Dwayne Fox still on the run, the Sun Hill team face the problem of protecting their key witness. Fox's boss Marco Oliver is shocked at the killing, and volunteers to help set up a sting operation to catch the second suspect before the rival gangs can get to Alisha. Meanwhile, Alisha informs CID of further evidence that could lead to other possible suspects being detained for Carly's murder.

Nate and Emma investigate when Alisha Danniels is involved in a hit and run attack. When she regains consciousness in hospital, she reveals that the attack has left her too shaken and terrified to testify against Morientes and Fox - but she does identify the third man involved in Carly's death. Emma and Nate trace the vehicle, and score a lucky bonus in identifying an ammunition seller who gives them the names of all the gun dealers on the Jasmine Allen estate.

Tension mounts at the start of the trial of Fox and Morientes for the murder of Carly Samuels, and Grace is shocked to encounter an old flame in the courtroom - the barrister working for the prosecution, who happens to be her ex-partner. Smithy is furious to learn a key witness has retracted his statement, and sets out with Emma to persuade Alisha Danniels to testify instead. Back at the station, Nate and Diane book in a man who has been up his pregnant girlfriend - only for him to smash his head against the wall of his cell, and claim that Nate attacked him.

As Smithy is driving the key prosecution witness to court, he is run off the road by an unknown assailant. However, he manages to get his witness to court to testify against Fox and Morientes after Tony rescues the crash victims from the overturned car. An investigation into the crash leads to vital new evidence, and a dramatic courtroom confession. Defence barrister Sunil Davdra pulls Alisha's testimony apart, but the case takes another surprising turn before a verdict is reached. On the Jasmine Allen estate, Beth and Reg find themselves barricaded in the mobile police unit as rioting breaks out.

Following a string of humiliating set-ups by teenagers, Gina clamps down on hoax calls and assigns Will to screen all incoming messages, but the plaintive voice of a youngster claiming he and his brother have been kidnapped by their father convinces Nikki it's the real thing. Confronting the suicidal parent at the docks, she persuades him to release the children - but only on condition she takes their place in his car. When Callum and Tony respond to the scene of a hoax call, they are pelted with eggs by a bunch of youths. Later, when they respond to a reported sighting of a body in the river, they are hit with water balloons - and decide to fight fire with fire.

When Callum and Tony respond to the scene of a hoax call, they are pelted with eggs by a bunch of youths. Later, when they respond to a reported sighting of a body in the river, they are hit with water balloons - and decide to fight fire with fire.

Sally and Ben stop a twelve-year-old boy driving a stolen car, and investigate claims that the boy's father is being threatened by a known violent offender. Later, they find the father at the wheel of his car - stabbed. Meanwhile, Nate and Beth attempt to stop a fleeing suspect in a landrover. Stevie and Terry investigate the provenance of an explicit film featuring a well known local celebrity, and arrive at the flat of one of the stars, only to find him with a tattoo of the word 'SCUM' carved into his head with a knife.

When a homeless man is hit on the head by a tonne of 'bricks', the team discover that they are actually bags of cocaine jettisoned by Ben's protege Liam Harvey. When the lad is later found badly beaten, the kindly copper is incensed, assuming his father Bob is responsible. Under provocation during the interrogation, he puts his career on the line by head-butting the suspect, and it's left to Callum to save Ben's skin when DPS officers arrive to investigate the resulting complaint. Smithy finds Callum in a compromising position with an evidence bag.

Callum and Sally investigate an assault on a young woman, found in an alleyway outside a club. The pair suspect rape, but the victim insists that she was the victim of a mugging - and club owner Iain Andain looks certain to escape rape and assault charges for the third time in his seedy career when Sam agrees to drop charges in return for information about a major drug dealer. Callum is determined the unsavoury lowlife won't get away with it yet again, and encourages his indignant young constables Will and Ben to dish out their own brand of justice. Meanwhile, a drugs raid planned by Max, Stevie and Terry is a bust, after they discover that they were fed false intelligence.

A woman reports seeing a body being thrown into the river, and a search organised by Roger and Beth recovers the remains of a hospital doctor, recently exonerated from charges of professional negligence after losing a patient on the operating table. Seemingly unimpressed by his method of working, Roger is surprised when Crime Scene Examiner Eddie Olosunje discovers that the man had been suffering from MS, and had argued with a colleague about concealing his plight from the General Medical Council.

Heaton upsets everyone by deciding to join his PCs on the beat, which couldn't come at a worse time for Beth and Emma, who are suffering from a hangover after a night out on the town. Fortunately, Gina and Nikki trail them and step in when an arrest has to be made at Canley Market. Roger and Nate find a delivery driver beaten up by a truck-jacker who has made off with a consignment of electrical goods. After hearing the news that one of his old friends from Barton Street has been stabbed after bing confronted by an angry suspect with a knife, Reg considers his future at Sun Hill.

When Will, Ben, Callum and Sally are called to a disturbance at a nightclub, Sally ends up being rescued from a brawl by an undercover officer, Andrew Tipping, from another station, only to learn he was the instigator of the disturbance and in possession of cocaine. When he appeals to her to cover for him she makes a split-second decision that puts her career on the line. Meanwhile, Jo deals with a victim of the fight who reveals an obsessive desire to catch up with the dealer who sold drugs to his daughter.

Smithy answers a call about a pensioner who has been attacked during a burglary, so Stevie and Mickey set up a sting operation involving one of her neighbours, that reveals a well-established outfit selling stolen goods on the internet. When two hoodies previously seen arguing with the victim are eliminated from the inquiry, the officers are left with some unlikely suspects, reminding them how deceptive appearances can be. The team later decide to set up a sting operation to trap the thief red-handed.

Beth receives information on a major drug dealer, and volunteers to go undercover to collect more evidence. Max reluctantly agrees, and the plucky constable finds herself at a party, where she strikes up a friendship with DJ Lenny Jones, but has to leave in a hurry when she spots a man wielding a gun. An arrest follows, but loose ends mean she must play her role once more, putting herself into even more danger.

Thirteen-year-old Jenny Waterson attempts to commit suicide after being raped by a stranger named Craig, who groomed her on the internet, and CID are shocked to learn her best friend Shareen has disappeared after arranging to meet the same man. DI Phil Ashley of the Child Exploitation and Online Protection squad pursues the lead, and uncovers a paedophile network in operation, after uncovering CCTV footage of the man talking to Shareen.

Grace works with the Child Exploitation and Online Protection unit and discovers why the job makes Phil Ashley so moody, while the race is on to trace the man behind the paedophile network and rescue their victim Simon Thomas. However, before she can get to work, she is asked to listen to the advice of Supt. John Faraday, who briefs the team on how a paedophile network is set up. Terry interviews known sex offender Peter Williams for a second time, and blots his copybook by kneeing him in the groin, but his dogged detective work produces a result. Diane decides to take some time out to spend more time with her son.

Terry interviews known sex offender Peter Williams for a second time, and blots his copybook by kneeing him in the groin, but his dogged detective work produces a result. Diane decides to take some time out to spend more time with her son.

Stevie and Stuart set out to arrest the brothel keeper, but the encounter takes a horrifying turn when the suspect brandishes a dirty heroin syringe, and stabs Stuart in the neck.

Stuart faces an anxious wait for the HIV test results after being stabbed in the neck with a dirty needle by Danny Peters. Jack is taken aback when the sergeant turns up for work as usual the next day - not least because he has struck a deal with Peters for inside information on a major heroin smuggling operation, and Stevie has volunteered to work underground in a high-risk sting. Stuart is upset when Jack agrees to say a good word for Peters in court, in exchange for helping to bust a major drugs smuggling gang.

Smithy and Will investigate when they find a former east end gangster seriously injured, and discover three generations of an East End criminal dynasty working together. Ageing gangster Johnnie Jackson, sensing the onset of Alzheimer's disease, tries to rescue his grandson from a life of crime, but the seeds of destruction are already sown as young Jacko finds himself working for ruthless drug dealer Roger Hutton. However, before he can stop a bad turn of events, Jacko's body is found in a pool of blood.

Following an armed robbery on an antiques shop, Jack agrees, under Heaton's supervision, to go undercover to nail the dealer responsible for selling the goods - a rogue called Roy Summers, who killed a police officer some years ago and walked free from court on a technicality. The sting goes wrong when Jack loses touch with his back-up team and faces a stern test of his expertise in bric-a-brac. However, the operation proves a little more risky than first thought, when it is discovered that the antiques are being used to ferry drugs through a network of country-wide dealers.

Emma and Sally are called to a break-in, where the intruders have run off, having been fought off by the householder. Sally and Tony later come across one of the intruders, who has been badly injured. The householder is arrested for attempted murder, but claims he only hit out with a hammer to fight off the intruders and protect his daughters. Emma follows a hunch he is telling the truth and sets up a ruse with fellow officers to prove his innocence. While the team celebrate the result, by-the-book sergeant Callum is clearly not happy about his junior colleague's maverick methods.

DC Jacob Banks joins the Sun Hill watch in time to help a hung-over Mickey investigate the murder of a private detective, who had been looking for a missing teenage girl at the time of his death, and soon establishes himself as a member of the team. Meanwhile, Callum continues to single Emma out for harsh treatment among all his constables, and Sally catches the backlash of her resentment. However, Emma later lives to regret informing Gina of the situation.

Sally works undercover in a City trading house to investigate the disappearance of twenty-year-old Geraldine Lawson, that may involve one of a group of traders. She arranges to go drinking with three of Geraldine's colleagues - all suspects who were with her on the night she went missing. After being taken off routine work, Emma joins the operation as a 'friend' for the night out and proves she'll stop at nothing to get the truth out of her chosen target and put Callum in his place.

Emma and Sally are first to respond when two massive fertilizer explosions rock Sun Hill, killing seven bystanders stone dead. John and Gina monitor the shocking scenes of carnage from the station, while Callum takes charge on the ground, directing his team to deal with multiple casualties, confused and hysterical survivors and petty thieves taking advantage of the chaos. When it becomes clear a pervert has been posing as a doctor to molest injured women, Callum loses his grip and vents his fury on the man, but his troubles have only just begun. As Emma and Sally investigate a third incident at Industry House, the pair manage to evacuate the building, but a bomb goes off before Emma can escape - and tragedy strikes.

When it becomes clear a pervert has been posing as a doctor to molest injured women, Callum loses his grip and vents his fury on the man, but his troubles have only just begun. As Emma and Sally investigate a third incident at Industry House, the pair manage to evacuate the building, but a bomb goes off before Emma can escape - and tragedy strikes.

The Sun Hill team struggle to come to terms with Emma's death, following a series of explosions that have rocked the borough. Callum's guilty feelings lead to a fight with Smithy, while Sally can only weep after arresting chief suspect Carl Adams. DI Karen Lacey of the Counter Terrorism Unit arrives to take charge over the case, and Kezia and Mickey are tasked to search the bomb-maker's home - only to find that they have walked into a booby trap.

Callum vows to trace the bomber responsible for his colleague's death, and after taking some time out to mourn, he, Sally, Ben and Will are asked to investigate another bomb - due to go off in three hours time - and it gives the plucky sergeant a chance to demonstrate his bravery once more. CID are horrified to realise that they have had the killer in custody all along, and let him get away - while the rest of the Sun Hill watch pays their respects at Emma's graveside.

Neil returns to work, determined to bring some discipline back into CID. He and Stevie investigate the apparent disappearance of a groom on his wedding day, after a burglary at his house. However, his day goes from bad to worse when the jilted bride takes a swing at her cheating bridesmaid and catches the unwary detective in the crossfire. His mood is not improved when it transpires the errant groom has beaten a gay man unconscious and the victim's partner - a Kylie Minogue impersonator - won't submit to questioning without a chase through the streets in full drag.

Nikki and Roger encounter a young lad who has been beaten up, and discover his house has been ransacked, and that his family are under pressure from a loan shark seeking to recoup a vast sum of money. The officers clash over how to run the case when drugs are discovered in the boy's room. Further investigations by Jo and Stevie reveal the boy's estranged father has been involved in a drug dealers' turf war and has disappeared without trace. When a body is found, it becomes clear the frightened youngster knows more than he's letting on.

Tensions rise between Terry and Max when they find themselves stuck in a traffic jam, and are helpless to intervene as car-jackers drag a woman from her vehicle, stabbing her fatally. Increasing conflict between the two detectives compromises their subsequent investigation into an international car theft racket, and the atmosphere deteriorates as the detectives work on the case. Sam has to separate them when they come to blows, and Neil struggles to regain the confidence to bring order to CID.

Sally and Beth discover a man, Alan Marlowe, found badly beaten had argued with his runaway daughter Lucy the night before. As the team uncover some interesting facts relating to the investigation, Beth develops a soft spot for the girl, but can't get much out of her about the incident and her touchingly protective boyfriend Mark denies suggestions he might be involved. The family clearly have a lot to hide and Sally warns Beth not to get personally involved.

Lucy Burton's body is found in an apparent suicide, but forensic analysis reveals she was murdered. A distraught Beth has the unenviable task of quizzing her friends and searching the house, while Terry discovers the victim's sinister housemate Mark Lawrence has a history of beguiling and controlling girls. When evidence linking to her boyfriend being the murder, the Sun Hill watch mount an all-out search for him.

New probationary constables Leon Taylor, Millie Brown and Arun Ghir quickly get into their stride when a stolen cutting torch is used in a bank robbery. Leon makes his first arrest, as the bumbling duo who tunnelled into the bank are traced, but the money has disappeared - and the mastermind behind the operation is still on the loose. But when Millie and Arun discover who is responsible for the crime, they are shocked to the core.

A woman's body is found on a landfill site, and Neil and Kezia learn the victim had been involved in an argument at a house party on the night of her death. Three suspects emerge from the story of her tangled love life, but the investigation reaches deadlock when all three seem to have cast-iron alibis. Attempting to crack the case in his own sophisticated way, Neil decides to set up one of the suspects, in order to try and catch him red-handed.

New recruit PC Mel Ryder accompanies Smithy to interview an ex-soldier accused of trashing his own home. The Iraq War veteran admits to involvement with a gun-running operation, but makes his escape after handcuffing the terrified pair at gun-point. When a young boy, Emile Grover, is found with a loaded gun, he is brought into the station for questioning - but reveals that he was asked to carry the gun by local gang leader Andre Tyrell. When Emile later goes missing, Smithy fears his life may be in danger.
